114
00:08:09,598 --> 00:08:11,078
So what is machine learning?

115
00:08:12,167 --> 00:08:17,028
The part of artificial intelligence that has recently evolved exponentially is called machine

116
00:08:17,068 --> 00:08:17,389
learning.

117
00:08:17,829 --> 00:08:20,810
I will try to explain here the core concepts of machine learning.

118
00:08:20,850 --> 00:08:26,392
There's nothing technical here, but it is important to understand the data-driven application

119
00:08:26,612 --> 00:08:32,874
and approach of machine learning because it's key in the change we have to lead in production.

120
00:08:34,255 --> 00:08:38,376
Just raising hand, how many of you are already familiar with those concepts?

121
00:08:40,497 --> 00:08:40,697
Okay.

122
00:08:42,227 --> 00:08:47,349
So half of you will have to bear with some simplification

123
00:08:47,389 --> 00:08:49,650
that we'll have to make to explain

124
00:08:49,670 --> 00:08:50,711
what machine learning is.

125
00:08:51,271 --> 00:08:54,252
But I think it's important that we are all on the same page.

126
00:08:55,193 --> 00:08:57,674
Here is a simple prediction problem.

127
00:08:58,874 --> 00:09:00,935
If I'm asking you the value of f,

128
00:09:01,695 --> 00:09:08,398
your brain will analyze the data, decompose it,

129
00:09:09,379 --> 00:09:10,099
and generalize.

130
00:09:10,804 --> 00:09:13,925
an approximation, this is a generalization step.

131
00:09:14,685 --> 00:09:18,265
And then extrapolate, which is a prediction step.

132
00:09:19,986 --> 00:09:22,766
This very simple example illustrates two key concepts.

133
00:09:22,946 --> 00:09:28,707
First, the principle of a given data set that illustrates a desired behavior.

134
00:09:30,308 --> 00:09:39,429
And a learning algorithm that uses this data set to create a function that enables generalization

135
00:09:39,650 --> 00:09:40,510
to new inputs.

136
00:09:41,843 --> 00:09:43,504
And this is what machine learning does.

137
00:09:44,485 --> 00:09:47,026
But we use it for a problem a bit more complex

138
00:09:47,106 --> 00:09:48,787
than drawing a straight line.

139
00:09:49,767 --> 00:09:51,548
It uses three dangerous ingredients.

140
00:09:51,928 --> 00:09:55,010
First, a data set that represents the desired outcome.

141
00:09:56,110 --> 00:09:59,772
A neural network, which is a transformation function,

142
00:10:00,072 --> 00:10:01,973
basically a set of matrices.

143
00:10:03,233 --> 00:10:05,254
And also learning algorithms that

144
00:10:05,314 --> 00:10:07,755
parameterizes the transformation function,

145
00:10:08,116 --> 00:10:09,957
basically fill the matrices.

146
00:10:12,091 --> 00:10:17,034
So the data set is used as a set of input and output examples

147
00:10:17,494 --> 00:10:18,555
for a neural network.

148
00:10:19,896 --> 00:10:22,397
The algorithms measure the difference

149
00:10:22,838 --> 00:10:26,860
between the network output and the desired output,

150
00:10:27,140 --> 00:10:29,061
or in other words, what we call the ground truth.

151
00:10:30,042 --> 00:10:32,484
The process is obviously iterative in a loop

152
00:10:32,604 --> 00:10:36,026
that is called the training phase that can last hours,

153
00:10:36,086 --> 00:10:37,166
days, or even weeks.

154
00:10:38,905 --> 00:10:42,008
And based on those examples, it sets the weights of neurons,

155
00:10:42,168 --> 00:10:44,690
which means filling matrices, or in other words,

156
00:10:45,070 --> 00:10:46,891
parameterizes the neural network.

157
00:10:47,712 --> 00:10:51,475
Somewhat, the machine learns based on examples.

158
00:10:53,236 --> 00:10:55,278
The neural network is then ready to generalize

159
00:10:55,438 --> 00:10:56,439
as a predictive model.

160
00:10:56,499 --> 00:10:59,941
So a new input provides an output.

161
00:11:00,862 --> 00:11:04,785
But because machine learning approximates the ground truth

162
00:11:05,065 --> 00:11:06,866
based on its observation.

163
00:11:08,133 --> 00:11:10,314
The output always comes with stats,

164
00:11:10,655 --> 00:11:15,198
like precision, confidence, recall, and et cetera.

165
00:11:17,640 --> 00:11:20,302
It is also important to note that simple data

166
00:11:20,382 --> 00:11:23,624
sets for simple input treatments have been used for decades.

167
00:11:24,485 --> 00:11:27,907
For example, for handwritten characters recognitions.

168
00:11:28,447 --> 00:11:32,670
So what if we use complex data, like images or sounds,

169
00:11:32,770 --> 00:11:34,992
or even what is apparently the biggest

170
00:11:35,052 --> 00:11:36,693
challenge on the internet, which is?

171
00:11:37,560 --> 00:11:40,501
which is recognizing pictures of cats.

172
00:11:42,641 --> 00:11:43,561
The principle is the same,

173
00:11:44,342 --> 00:11:46,482
but the models to extract features

174
00:11:46,862 --> 00:11:48,243
or generalize is different.

175
00:11:49,883 --> 00:11:52,744
The key idea is to decompose complex data

176
00:11:53,044 --> 00:11:55,004
into smaller manageable features.

177
00:11:55,085 --> 00:11:57,265
And because there are many hidden layers,

178
00:11:57,825 --> 00:11:59,186
it is called deep learning.

179
00:12:00,906 --> 00:12:04,467
What is interesting though is that the mathematical methods

180
00:12:04,947 --> 00:12:06,928
behind deep learning are not new.

181
00:12:07,823 --> 00:12:14,306
However, the first applicable results of deep learning, real applicable results, happened

182
00:12:14,607 --> 00:12:14,747
in 2010.

183
00:12:15,927 --> 00:12:18,929
The missing link was computing power.

184
00:12:21,891 --> 00:12:23,131
It works exactly the same way.

185
00:12:24,192 --> 00:12:31,756
The algorithm extracts features from the data and then populates different layers of neurons.

186
00:12:32,396 --> 00:12:36,258
Each layer represents a step in the feature extraction.

187
00:12:37,638 --> 00:12:40,199
When the neural network sees a new picture,

188
00:12:40,300 --> 00:12:43,922
it predicts whether the image is a cat or not

189
00:12:44,902 --> 00:12:47,724
by extracting the features from the input data.

190
00:12:51,647 --> 00:12:55,709
Simple data sets require simple machine learning problems

191
00:12:55,889 --> 00:12:56,410
and models.

192
00:12:57,210 --> 00:13:01,233
Complex data sets require more complex algorithms

193
00:13:01,593 --> 00:13:05,295
to populate hidden layers that serves as feature extraction.

194
00:13:07,162 --> 00:13:10,142
And this is why we say it is data-driven.

195
00:13:11,723 --> 00:13:16,004
Instead of implementing a specific outcome or behavior,

196
00:13:16,584 --> 00:13:21,245
if this, then that, we focus on the right data

197
00:13:21,305 --> 00:13:23,446
set that represents this behavior.

198
00:13:24,786 --> 00:13:26,907
And because machine learning always

199
00:13:27,027 --> 00:13:29,867
makes a prediction when new data is shown,

200
00:13:30,488 --> 00:13:33,288
it is extremely important that the data set reflects

201
00:13:33,588 --> 00:13:36,029
the future usage of your network.

202
00:13:36,580 --> 00:13:39,002
or it will lead to very unexpected results.

203
00:13:40,463 --> 00:13:45,087
If the neural network learns from pictures of ducks and beavers,

204
00:13:47,249 --> 00:13:53,434
showing a platypus, believe me, will lead to interesting but likely unexpected results.

205
00:13:57,917 --> 00:14:00,099
Now, why is it important?

206
00:14:00,821 --> 00:14:05,283
Because as game developers, we have many types of interesting complex data,

207
00:14:05,323 --> 00:14:08,204
like sound, animation, textures, models,

208
00:14:08,904 --> 00:14:12,806
which means we have a lot of data that is relevant for deep learning,

209
00:14:13,526 --> 00:14:16,428
and many possible usages for predictions,

210
00:14:16,688 --> 00:14:22,310
like asset classification, behaviors programming, or even asset generations.

211
00:14:24,611 --> 00:14:27,192
It works for simple or complex datasets,

212
00:14:27,392 --> 00:14:30,013
but now, what if we just...

213
00:14:31,104 --> 00:14:34,446
don't have the data, which happens often.

214
00:14:36,367 --> 00:14:41,551
Well, we have simulations, and we can use some specific kind of algorithms

215
00:14:42,191 --> 00:14:43,872
called reinforcement learning.

216
00:14:46,053 --> 00:14:52,497
The idea is simple. An agent is given a set of actions, goals, and rewards,

217
00:14:52,878 --> 00:14:57,821
when it finds a way to reach its goal. We also set punishments when it reaches

218
00:14:57,921 --> 00:15:00,022
some specific outcomes, when it fails.

219
00:15:01,338 --> 00:15:09,402
Then, the agent tries many different things in the simulations or in the game to maximize its rewards.

220
00:15:12,784 --> 00:15:18,747
After a while, by trial and errors, the algorithm finds the right strategy.

221
00:15:22,529 --> 00:15:30,253
The strategy populates the neural network. This can be seen as creating the right data sets that map

222
00:15:30,707 --> 00:15:38,753
states to actions. So when a new situation is given to the neural network, it predicts

223
00:15:39,193 --> 00:15:41,255
what is the best action to take.

224
00:15:46,940 --> 00:15:53,425
So here are the main things you should remember for this section. But the most important part

225
00:15:54,045 --> 00:15:58,669
is that more than a technology, it is a new way to think.

226
00:15:59,388 --> 00:16:02,389
It's less about programming a behavior.

227
00:16:03,350 --> 00:16:05,591
It's more about choosing the right data

228
00:16:05,691 --> 00:16:09,873
set that illustrates the behavior with the objective

229
00:16:10,273 --> 00:16:11,153
to generalize it.

230
00:16:14,615 --> 00:16:17,737
So I hope you get a better idea now of the implications

231
00:16:18,037 --> 00:16:18,997
of being data-driven.

232
00:16:19,798 --> 00:16:22,159
It is not something that happens behind the scene

233
00:16:22,539 --> 00:16:25,600
or under the hood or only for technical people.

234
00:16:26,118 --> 00:16:29,821
It's really a significant shift in the way most of us work,

235
00:16:30,742 --> 00:16:33,164
and it has strong production implications.

236
00:16:35,326 --> 00:16:38,829
Traditional approaches require a lot of programming.

237
00:16:39,429 --> 00:16:41,691
They provide with complete control

238
00:16:42,372 --> 00:16:44,053
in a very manageable environment.

239
00:16:46,255 --> 00:16:51,660
However, they are difficult to maintain and to scale up.

240
00:16:52,443 --> 00:16:54,724
This is a very simplified version of a tree.

241
00:16:54,744 --> 00:16:58,186
If you worked with animation trees, you know what I mean.

242
00:17:00,307 --> 00:17:03,309
Conversely, data-driven approaches

243
00:17:03,889 --> 00:17:07,932
lead to less programming and offer less control.

244
00:17:09,492 --> 00:17:13,215
Huge amount of data are passed through math and intuition,

245
00:17:13,675 --> 00:17:16,657
which requires to juggle between hard science

246
00:17:17,157 --> 00:17:18,838
and some sort of alchemy.

247
00:17:19,418 --> 00:17:21,099
But the rewards.

248
00:17:21,887 --> 00:17:26,530
is significant, as they lead to unprecedented capacities

249
00:17:26,570 --> 00:17:29,353
to scale up with very low maintenance efforts,

250
00:17:29,533 --> 00:17:32,235
because it relies solely on training data.

251
00:17:33,116 --> 00:17:35,237
If you think about that, when you

252
00:17:35,257 --> 00:17:36,679
want to implement a new behavior,

253
00:17:37,659 --> 00:17:41,142
it only requires to add new data and retrain the model.

